  "prompt": "What do you put in a resignation letter?",
  "response": "A resignation letter should be professional, clear, and concise. Here's a breakdown of the key elements to include:\n\n**1. Your Contact Information (Optional, but Recommended):**\n\n*   Your Name\n*   Your Address\n*   Your Phone Number\n*   Your Email Address\n    *   *Reason:*  This makes it easy for your employer to contact you if they need to send you final paperwork or have any questions.\n\n**2. Date:**\n\n*   The date you are writing the letter.\n\n**3. Employer Contact Information:**\n\n*   Name of your manager or HR representative\n*   Title of your manager or HR representative\n*   Company Name\n*   Company Address\n\n**4. Statement of Resignation:**\n\n*   Clearly state your intention to resign from your position.  Be direct and unambiguous.\n\n    *   *Example:* \"Please accept this letter as formal notification that I am resigning from my position as [Your Job Title] at [Company Name].\"\n\n**5. Effective Date:**\n\n*   Specify the exact date your resignation will take effect.  This is crucial.  Give the amount of notice specified in your employment contract or company policy (typically two weeks in the US).\n\n    *   *Example:* \"My last day of employment will be [Date].\"  OR \"My resignation will be effective on [Date].\"\n\n**6. Expression of Gratitude (Optional but Highly Recommended):**\n\n*   Thank your employer for the opportunity to work at the company.  Be genuine, even if your experience wasn't perfect.  Focus on positive aspects or learning experiences.\n\n    *   *Example:* \"I would like to thank you for the opportunity to have worked at [Company Name] for the past [Number] years. I have gained valuable experience and appreciate the opportunities I've been given.\"\n    *   *Example:* \"I have enjoyed my time at [Company Name] and am grateful for the experiences and relationships I've built.\"\n\n**7. Offer to Assist with Transition (Optional but a Good Idea):**\n\n*   Briefly offer to help with the transition process, such as training your replacement or documenting your responsibilities.  This demonstrates professionalism and a willingness to leave on good terms.  Only offer this if you are genuinely willing and able to do so.\n\n    *   *Example:* \"I am happy to assist in the transition process to ensure a smooth handover of my responsibilities.  Please let me know how I can be of assistance during my remaining time here.\"\n    *   *Example:* \"I am willing to help train my replacement and document my processes to ensure a seamless transition.\"\n\n**8. Closing Salutation:**\n\n*   Use a professional closing salutation.\n\n    *   *Examples:*\n        *   Sincerely,\n        *   Respectfully,\n        *   Best regards,\n        *   Yours truly,\n\n**9. Signature:**\n\n*   Sign your name (if a physical letter).\n\n**10. Typed Name:**\n\n*   Type your name below your signature.\n\n**Example Resignation Letter:**\n\n```\n[Your Name]\n[Your Address]\n[Your Phone Number]\n[Your Email Address]\n\n[Date]\n\n[Manager's Name]\n[Manager's Title]\n[Company Name]\n[Company Address]\n\nDear [Manager's Name],\n\nPlease accept this letter as formal notification that I am resigning from my position as [Your Job Title] at [Company Name], effective [Date - usually two weeks from the date of the letter].\n\nThank you for the opportunity to have worked at [Company Name] for the past [Number] years.  I have learned a great deal and appreciate the experiences I've gained.\n\nI am happy to assist in the transition process in any way I can to ensure a smooth handover of my responsibilities.\n\nSincerely,\n\n[Your Signature]\n\n[Your Typed Name]\n```\n\n**Key Considerations and Tips:**\n\n*   **Keep it positive:** Avoid negativity or complaining about your job, coworkers, or the company, even if you had a negative experience.  This is not the place for grievances.\n*   **Be concise:** Aim for a one-page letter.\n*   **Proofread carefully:**  Check for any spelling or grammatical errors.  Have someone else read it over as well.\n*   **Follow company policy:**  Be sure to adhere to your company's specific requirements for resignation, if any.\n*   **Deliver the letter properly:**  Follow your company's procedure for submitting your resignation.  Typically, you'll give it to your manager directly.  Consider sending a copy to HR as well.\n*   **Maintain a professional tone:** Even if you're leaving for a better opportunity, be respectful and gracious. You never know when you might cross paths with these people again.\n*   **Don't burn bridges:** You might need a reference from this employer in the future.\n*   **Think about your reasons for leaving:**  While you don't need to state them in the letter, be prepared to discuss them in person with your manager if asked. Keep your explanation professional and constructive.\n*   **Consult legal advice if necessary:** If you have any concerns about your employment agreement or potential legal issues, consult with an attorney.\n*   **Digital Resignation Letters (Email):**  If you're submitting your resignation via email, the same principles apply.  The formatting will be slightly different.  Omit the return address and company address. The subject line should be clear and concise (e.g., \"Resignation - [Your Name]\").\n*   **Before submitting:** Review your employee handbook and employment agreement to ensure you are following any required procedures or guidelines.\n\nBy following these guidelines, you can create a professional and effective resignation letter that helps you leave your job on good terms. Good luck with your next endeavor!\n",
